{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4eb5dd89-d9a5-4063-bc33-281eb8c1e975","content":"**Exit code 8** is MTP's \"no tests discovered\" error — a deliberate behavioral difference from VSTest, which returned 0 in that case.\n\nSince your tests are conditionally compiled (`#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS`), configurations without that symbol produce zero tests, triggering exit code 8.\n\n**Fix options (pick one):**\n\n1. **CLI flag** — tell MTP zero tests is OK:\n   ```\n   dotnet test -- --minimum-expected-tests 0\n   ```\n\n2. **Environment variable** — useful in CI pipelines:\n   ```\n   TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE=8\n   ```\n\n3. **Per-project via runsettings** — add a `testconfig.runsettings`:\n   ```xml\n   <RunSettings>\n     <TestingPlatform>\n       <MinimumExpectedTests>0</MinimumExpectedTests>\n     </TestingPlatform>\n   </RunSettings>\n   ```\n   then: `dotnet test -s testconfig.runsettings`\n\nOption **1** is the simplest. Want me to apply any of these to your project?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88778b83-3f75-439b-8fda-434561d20282","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the issue clearly. The project uses MTP (`EnableMSTestRunner=true`) and has conditional compilation (`#if INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS`). When `INCLUDE_SLOW_TESTS` is not defined, there are zero tests, and MTP returns exit code 8 (which means \"no tests found\"), whereas VSTest returned 0 in this case.\n\nThe fix is straightforward: set the `--ignore-exit-code` option or use the environment variable `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE` to treat exit code 8 as success, OR configure it in the project file.\n\nActually, the best project-level fix is to add a property or use the `--minimum-expected-tests 0` option. Let me think about the cleanest approach.\n\n\nFor MTP, exit code 8 means \"zero tests ran.\" I can fix this at the CI pipeline level by passing `--ignore-exit-code 8` to the `dotnet test` command or setting the `TESTINGPLATFORM_EXITCODE_IGNORE` environment variable, or at the project level by configuring MTP to accept zero tests as a valid outcome.\n\nThe cleanest approach is passing `--minimum-expected-tests 0` as a platform argument after `--` in the dotnet test command, or configuring it through a `.runsettings` file or MSBuild properties.","outputTokens":941,"requestId":"CFC4:14268C:E27913D:FBA123B:69EC0FCA"},"id":"f9459762-6709-4ff5-b716-7cc4d81e71df","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:50:41.189Z","parentId":"e02dc7ea-e427-4fdb-892d-8ac3333b3fff"}
